\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
6.
 Policy Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy establishes the Configuration Control Authority (CCA) function,
 the Request for Change (RFC) record structure,
 rollback obligations,
 Post-Implementation Review (PIR) requirements,
 and the conditions under which County Manager consultation is mandatory before a change may proceed.
 Standard change authorization is captured within the work order per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Service Request Fulfillment Policy) mechanics.
 Significant and Emergency change records are standalone RFC records that exist alongside,
 but separately from,
 any associated work order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.1 Change Categories
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All changes to production systems,
 infrastructure,
 configurations,
 and software within the Information Operations Department's technology environment shall be classified into one of three categories prior to initiation:
 Standard,
 Significant,
 or Emergency.
 All Information Operations Personnel shall determine the classification before initiating any change activity.
 Changes entering the change management process from any source —
 including remediations authorized under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Problem Management Policy) —
 shall be classified and authorized under this policy.
 The Problem management authorization confirms that the remediation addresses the identified root cause;
 the change management authorization under this policy confirms that the change can be safely implemented in the production environment.
 Both authorizations are required before implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Standard Change
\series default
:
 A Standard change is a low-risk,
 pre-approved change type for which a documented procedure exists in the Knowledge Base under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 A change type qualifies as Standard only if a pre-approved procedure for that change type is documented in the Knowledge Base;
 if no qualifying procedure exists,
 the change shall be classified as Significant until such a procedure is established and documented.
 Standard changes shall not require a per-instance standalone RFC record;
 authorization shall be captured within the associated work order per Section 6.2.
 Standard change examples include routine patching,
 password resets,
 and network printer additions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Significant Change
\series default
:
 A Significant change is any change that materially alters the County's operational technology environment and does not qualify as Standard or Emergency.
 Significant changes align with the "non-routine or significant IT-initiated tasks" category established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.05"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 A standalone RFC record in the System of Engagement shall be submitted and CCA authorization shall be obtained prior to implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Change
\series default
:
 An Emergency change is an unplanned change that shall be implemented immediately to restore service or address a critical security threat,
 where the time required to complete standard RFC and CCA review before acting would materially extend the duration or severity of the impact.
 Emergency changes shall be designated in accordance with Section 6.2.
 Implementation may precede the formal RFC record;
 catch-up documentation obligations are defined in Section 6.3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Change Authorization and CCA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
CCA is a function,
 not a title or organizational body.
 It is fulfilled as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For 
\series bold
Standard
\series default
 changes,
 the Assistant IT Director holds CCA authority by reference to standing authority under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For 
\series bold
Significant
\series default
 changes,
 the IT Director holds CCA authority.
 The IT Director may delegate CCA authority for Significant changes to the Assistant IT Director through either of two mechanisms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Per-instance delegation
\series default
:
 The IT Director issues explicit written delegation for a specific change or class of changes,
 documented at the time it is issued and specifying the scope to which it applies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Standing delegation
\series default
:
 The IT Director may establish standing CCA delegation to the Assistant IT Director for Significant changes that satisfy all of the following criteria:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The change affects only internal IT infrastructure with no cross-departmental service impact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The change has no Criminal Justice Information (CJI) nexus.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The change does not meet any County Manager consultation trigger defined in Section 6.6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The change does not involve decommission or replacement of a system designated as operationally critical infrastructure by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The standing delegation shall be documented in the standing Delegation of Authority Order reviewed annually under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The IT Director retains personal CCA authority for all changes involving CJI systems,
 cross-departmental impact,
 County Manager consultation triggers,
 critical infrastructure decommission,
 and any change the IT Director elects to review.
 The IT Director may revoke or modify the standing delegation at any time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Implementation of a Significant change without prior CCA authorization constitutes a compliance failure under Section 6.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For 
\series bold
Emergency
\series default
 changes,
 the IT Director,
 the Assistant IT Director,
 or the active Incident Commander may designate a change as Emergency.
 Emergency designation serves as a trigger for expedited change review and implementation;
 it does not itself constitute CCA authorization.
 The IT Director or Assistant IT Director shall hold provisional CCA authority to authorize immediate implementation of the designated Emergency change.
 Provisional CCA authority authorizes immediate implementation pending the catch-up CCA review defined below;
 if the catch-up review countermands the change,
 remediation obligations attach.
 Where the IT Director is the designating authority,
 that designation constitutes provisional CCA authorization.
 The IT Director may countermand any Emergency change designation;
 the countermand shall be documented in the change record at the time it is issued.
 Catch-up CCA review shall be completed by the IT Director within twenty-four (24) hours of the emergency change,
 or by noon on the next business day,
 whichever is later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The County Manager consultation obligations defined in Section 6.6 shall be satisfied prior to CCA authorization for Significant changes.
 For Emergency changes meeting Section 6.6 triggers,
 County Manager notification shall occur no later than four (4) hours following the initiation of implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 RFC Structure and Requirements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Standard Changes
\series default
:
 No standalone RFC record shall be required.
 Authorization shall be documented within the associated work order and shall include:
 the basis for Standard classification,
 and a reference to the Knowledge Base procedure under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.13"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 that qualifies this change type as Standard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Significant Changes
\series default
:
 A standalone RFC record shall be created in the System of Engagement prior to implementation.
 The RFC shall include at minimum:
 a description and scope of the change;
 a risk assessment;
 discrete,
 incremental implementation steps each with a defined rollback point;
 a rollback plan;
 anticipated impact and affected systems;
 the CCA authorization record;
 and County Manager consultation status where applicable under Section 6.6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Emergency Changes
\series default
:
 Implementation may precede the RFC record.
 A standalone RFC record shall be created in the System of Engagement within twenty-four (24) hours of the emergency change,
 or by noon on the next business day,
 whichever is later.
 This is the same clock as the CI record update obligation under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 and the catch-up CCA review obligation;
 all three obligations run concurrently on the same clock.
 The catch-up RFC shall document:
 all actions taken prior to record creation with the most precise timestamps recoverable;
 the conditions that justified Emergency designation;
 the CCA review outcome;
 and CI update confirmation per 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.08"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 Failure to complete catch-up RFC documentation or CCA review within this window constitutes a compliance failure under Section 6.8.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Rollback and Failed Change Protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Significant changes shall be structured as discrete,
 incremental steps,
 each with a defined rollback point.
 A single monolithic implementation is not permitted.
 The incremental step structure required in the RFC is the mechanism that makes rollback to a stable state operationally feasible;
 it is a design requirement of the change,
 not a documentation preference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A Significant change that fails mid-implementation shall be rolled back to the last stable incremental state immediately.
 Rollback shall not require additional authorization;
 it is the default response to implementation failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Director may authorize an alternative resolution path in lieu of rollback.
 That authorization shall be documented in the change record at the time it is issued,
 with rationale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The assigned technician shall evaluate a failed Significant change that required rollback against the Problem record spawn triggers defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:3.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 If the failure condition meets those triggers,
 a Problem record shall be created independently of the change management process.
 The change management process and the problem management process are complementary and shall not be merged or held pending the other's conclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Post-Implementation Review (PIR)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The assigned technician shall complete a PIR for all Significant and Emergency changes.
 The PIR shall be documented within the change record itself;
 no standalone record is required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The PIR shall address at minimum:
 whether the change achieved its intended outcome;
 whether any unintended impacts occurred;
 whether the rollback plan was invoked and,
 if so,
 why;
 and any follow-on actions required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The assigned technician shall complete and document the PIR within five (5) business days of implementation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 County Manager Consultation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The following conditions require mandatory County Manager consultation prior to implementation of a Significant change:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Changes to systems whose failure,
 compromise,
 or misconfiguration could directly affect the conduct,
 security,
 or publicly reported outcome of an election —
 such as voter registration systems,
 election night reporting systems,
 or network infrastructure dedicated to election administration.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Exclusion
\series default
:
 Routine support work for the Clerk's office,
 including workstation support,
 peripherals,
 and streaming setup,
 shall not qualify.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Changes that will cause planned downtime or degraded service visible to the public or to other County departments for more than one (1) business day.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Changes involving decommission or replacement of a system designated as operationally critical infrastructure by the IT Director.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Any change not meeting the above criteria that the IT Director determines carries political or notable operational implications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
County Manager consultation shall be documented in the RFC record prior to CCA authorization.
 Emergency changes meeting any of the above criteria shall notify the County Manager no later than four (4) hours following the initiation of implementation.
\end_layout

